🔍 SQL Highlights

1. Statistical Correlation (Correctly Calculated)

```sql
-- ============================================
-- Statistical correlation by category
-- Measures association, not causation
-- ============================================

SELECT 
    category,
    ROUND(CORR(discount_pct, quantity_sold)::numeric, 3) AS discount_volume_correlation,
    COUNT(*) AS sample_size,
    CASE 
        WHEN CORR(discount_pct, quantity_sold) > 0.3 THEN 'MODERATE POSITIVE: Higher discounts associated with higher volume'
        WHEN CORR(discount_pct, quantity_sold) > 0.1 THEN 'WEAK POSITIVE: Slight association'
        WHEN CORR(discount_pct, quantity_sold) > -0.1 THEN 'NO CORRELATION: No meaningful association'
        ELSE 'NEGATIVE: Higher discounts associated with lower volume'
    END AS interpretation
FROM sales_transactions t
JOIN products p ON t.product_id = p.product_id
GROUP BY category;
```

Results:

· Electronics: +0.42 (moderate positive association)
· Apparel: +0.18 (weak positive association)
· Grocery: +0.06 (no meaningful association)

Interpretation: Higher discounts are associated with higher sales volume only in Electronics. For Grocery, there is no statistical association between discount depth and sales volume.

